############################################################
# Header
############################################################
TEXT(beginproblem());

############################################################
# PG Setup Code
############################################################
Context()->operators->set(
'**' => {class => 'bizarro::BOP::power', isCommand => 1, perl=>undef},
'^' => {class => 'bizarro::BOP::power', isCommand => 1, perl=>undef},
);
Context()->variables()->are(x=>'Real',y=>'Real',z=>'Real');
Context()->variables->set(x=>{limits=>[0.1,2]});
Context()->variables->set(y=>{limits=>[0.1,2]});
Context()->variables->set(z=>{limits=>[0.1,2]});
$a[0]= Formula("4/y^6");
$a[1]= Formula("3z^2/(x^4y)");
$a[2]= Formula("40/x");
for my $i (0,1,2) {
    $evaluator[$i] = $a[$i] -> cmp(
       checker=>sub{
          my ( $correct, $student, $ansHash ) = @_;
          return 0 if $ansHash->{isPreview} || $correct != $student;
          $student = $ansHash->{student_formula};
          $correct = $correct->{original_formula} if defined $correct->{original_formula};
          $student = Formula("$student"); $correct = Formula("$correct");
          return 0 unless ($correct == $student);
          Context()->flags->set(bizarroPow=>1);
          delete $correct->{test_values};
          delete $student->{test_values};
          my $OK = (($correct == $student) or ($student == $correct));
          Context()->flags->set(bizarroPow=>0);
          Value::Error("Your answer is not in the required form yet") unless $OK;
          return $OK;
    });
};

############################################################
# Body
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML
a.  Write [`4y^{-6}`] without using negative exponents.

    [_]{$evaluator[0]}{12}

a.  Write [`\dfrac{ 3 x^{-4} }{ yz^{-2} }`] without using negative exponents.

    [_]{$evaluator[1]}{12}

a.  Simplify [`\left(-5x^{-5}\right)\left(-8x^4\right)`] and write it without using negative exponents.

    [_]{$evaluator[2]}{12}

END_PGML

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
a.  An exponent only applies to whatever it is "touching". In the expression [`4y^{-6}\text{,}`] only the [`y`] is affected by the exponent.

    [```\newcommand{\amp}{&}
    \begin{aligned}
    4y^{-6} \amp= 4\cdot \frac{1}{y^{6}}\\
    \amp= \frac{4}{y^6}
    \end{aligned}
    ```]

a.  Negative exponents tell us to move some variables between the numerator and denominator to make the exponents positive. The [`x^{-4}`] in the numerator should become [`x^4`] in the denominator. The [`z^{-2}`] in the denominator should become [`z^2`] in the numerator.

    [```\newcommand{\highlight}[1]{\mathchoice{\colorbox{lightsapphire}{$\displaystyle #1$}}{\colorbox{lightsapphire}{$\textstyle #1$}}{\colorbox{lightsapphire}{$\scriptstyle #1$}}{\colorbox{lightsapphire}{$\scriptscriptstyle #1$}}}
                      \frac{ 3 \highlight{x^{-4}} }{ y\highlight{z^{-2}} }=\frac{ 3 \highlight{z^{2}} }{ y\highlight{x^{4}} }
                    ```]

    Notice that the factors of [`3`] and [`y`] did not move, as both of those factors had positive exponents.

a.  The product of powers rule still applies, and we can add exponents even when one or both are negative:

    [```\newcommand{\amp}{&}
    \begin{aligned}
    \left(-5x^{-5}\right)\left(-8x^4\right)\amp=(-5)(-8)x^{-5}x^4\\
    \amp=40x^{-1}\\
    \amp=\frac{40}{x}
    \end{aligned}
    ```]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

